Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing. Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol. Defendant is not to enter any premises, other than a grocery store, that sells/serves alcohol beverages by the drink or into any liquor store.  The defendant is ordered to comply with CAM monitoring through Wisconsin Community Services.  Court orders the CAM monitor is to remain until further order of the Court.  Defendant to pay costs associated with CAM monitoring.  Defendant to be released during regular business hours only and is to report directly to Wisconsin Community Services upon release.

3:13 PM Defendant Kelly A Werner in court, in custody.  Attorney Luis Daniel Gutierrez in court for Kelly A Werner.  District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Jack Rieder.  Defendant is eligible for State Public Defender representation.  An attorney will be appointed. Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED. Court orders the CAM monitor is to remain until further order of the Court and does not authorize WCS to remove the monitor.  Court reserves the defendants right to bring a motion before this Court or the Trial Court if the defendant intends to enter in-patient treatment.
Hearing scheduled for October 27, 2022 at 10:00 am.
